I'm not sure what else you need. I'm not sure what is causing the failure or if I'm just calling the driver incorrectly. I've been using this driver for months so... well I'm not a newbie to this. That doesn't mean I didn't screw it up.

When using readPreference "nearest" at collection level, the driver always queries to primary (located in different region), even when a secondary is available in the same region).

let collection = db.collection("lists", {
  readPreference: "nearest"
})

However, if readPreference is specified in the connection url, the behaviour works as expected, where queries go to secondary that is located in the same region.

mongodb://user:password@db1.example.com,db2.example.com,db3.example.com/dbname?replicaSet=rs0

Problem is at line https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/blob/2.2/lib/gridfs-stream/upload.js#L147. The result is passed as first parameter (error) to the callback. 

Instead of:

    this.once('finish', callback);

the code should be:

    this.once('finish', function(result) { callback(null, result); });

Calling `MongoDB.connect(url, mongoOptions, cb);` callbacks with an error that is an EventEmitter. My full code is:

{code:js}
var MongoDB = require('mongodb');

var url = 'mongodb://<user>:<password>@<my-db-url>';
var mongoOptions = {
  db: { safe: true, native_parser: false },
  server: { autoReconnect: true, reconnectTries: Infinity },
  replSet: {}
};

var cb = function (e, r) { console.log('error:', e, 'res', r); };

MongoDB.connect(
  url,
  mongoOptions,
  cb
);
{code}

Happy to provide more context. I'm on node v4.6.1, connecting to mongo 3.2.8
